3. Process of Experimentation
Hypothesis 1: Traditional Social Feed with Educational Content

Experiment: Built content feed using typical algorithmic engagement optimization
Duration: 40 hours (Q1 2025)
Result: FAILED - Users consumed content but retention tests showed 12% knowledge retention
Learning: Engagement ≠ Learning. Infinite scroll works against cognitive consolidation.
Hypothesis 2: CLT-Based Learning Paths (No Social)

Experiment: Created personalized learning sequences using CLT principles but removed social features
Duration: 50 hours (Q2 2025)
Result: PARTIAL SUCCESS - 68% retention but 40% drop-off due to isolation/boredom
Learning: Social dynamics are necessary for sustained engagement, but must be designed differently
Hypothesis 3: Social Education Hybrid (CLT + Community)

Experiment: Integrated social dynamics (comments, shares, collaboration) with CLT-optimized content delivery
Duration: 80 hours (Q2-Q3 2025)
Result: SUCCESS - 71% retention + 82% completion rate + users reported "learned without noticing"
Learning: Social validation + cognitive optimization = sustainable learning behavior
Hypothesis 4: Token-Based Creator Payment (Learning Outcomes)

Experiment: Tested payment model where creators earn based on student skill development vs. views
Duration: 60 hours (Q3 2025)
Result: IN PROGRESS - Early data shows creators produce 30% higher quality content when paid for outcomes
Learning: Economic incentives drive behavior; optimizing for learning quality changes content strategy
Hypothesis 5: CLT-Based Cybersecurity UX

Experiment: Applied cognitive load reduction to security authentication and threat communication
Duration: 45 hours (Q3-Q4 2025)
Result: SUCCESS - Security compliance increased 56% when auth/alerts optimized for cognitive load
Learning: Most security failures stem from cognitive overload; CLT-based security is both safer AND easier
